$$ m_{{\text{r}}} = p_{{{\text{rp}}}} \cdot k_{{\text{p}}} \cdot m \cdot 365 = p_{{{\text{rp}}}} \cdot q_{{\text{T}}} \cdot \gamma _{{\text{p}}} \cdot m^{{1 - \kappa }} \cdot 365 $$\end{document}indicating that the mass released in a yearly sowing, clutch or litter (mr) scales to m with an exponent of 1−κ. Organisms with an intrinsic τr close to 1 year can exploit such synchronization most readily. Smaller species may somewhat postpone their reproduction, increasing the gonadic mass released. Larger species may do the opposite, decreasing the slope of the regression towards 3/4. Fitting Eq. 1 into 4 and writing m explicitly gives: 8\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
